    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Truth in Advertising Is Good for Judges, Too</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Raab letter opposes argument that there is a free speech right for misleading advertising in judicial elections (Aug 23 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''States Rein in Truth-Bending in Court Races'' (front page, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>Critics of the ''integrity drive'' present a specious argument when they talk about curtailment of First Amendment rights. It is understood that those rights are sacrificed when the greater community is at risk. We are forbidden to shout ''fire'' in a crowded theater when there is no fire. There are regulations on claims made on behalf of products and services in print and on television.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''States Rein in Truth-Bending in Court Races'' (front page, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>Critics of the ''integrity drive'' present a specious argument when they talk about curtailment of First Amendment rights. It is understood that those rights are sacrificed when the greater community is at risk. We are forbidden to shout ''fire'' in a crowded theater when there is no fire. There are regulations on claims made on behalf of products and services in print and on television.</p>
        <p>The greater ''democratic'' community is put at risk when blatant lies are told to ''sell'' candidates.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL RAAB  New York, Aug 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
